// RESEARCH
I started the project by researching a lot about how the Dijkstra algorithm works and how to implement it correctly in
our project.

// DIJKSTRA
I made a Dijkstra algorithm that finds the shortest path between two nodes in a graph and created new classes for it
to work in line with our project. I made a graph builder class for testing purposes and an Edge class.

The graph builder class makes it possible to connect two Nodes – both one way and two way (Directed graph and
undirected graph).
The edge class is used to create the edges between the nodes. It takes a source node and target node and adds a weight
to the edge. The weight is used to calculate the shortest path between two nodes. The Dijkstra algorithm uses a
priority queue to keep track of the nodes that are being explored and their distances from the source node.

// A*
When we had a working Dijkstra algorithm, I added heuristics to the priority queue making it an A* algorithm. The
heuristics are calculated as by prioritizing nodes that are closer to the target node. I have used haversine distance
to more accurately calculate the distance between the nodes.

When the A* algorithm was working, I added a boolean parameter to make it possible to turn on and off the heuristics.
This way we can use both Dijkstra and A*. This is only used for testing purposes.

Later in the project I upgraded the heuristic from a simple Euclidean approximation to a proper haversine calculation via
a shared UtilityTools class, which made the estimates much more accurate for geographic coordinates. I also tracked down
a critical bug where the source node was never added to the priority queue — it had been accidentally commented out,
which silently caused A* to return wrong results. Fixing that one line made everything work correctly.

// DEBUGGING HOTKEYS
After the A* algorithm was working, I started working on a way to find the nearest node the to cursor on the map. It
works by finding the Bounding Box that the cursor is in and then finding the nearest node to that bounding box. When
the node is found it creates a search radius around the cursor. The radius is calculated by the distance between the
cursor and the node and making a Bounding Box around the cursor. The Bounding Box is made by taking the cursor position
and finding the minimum and maximum latitudes and longitudes around that position.
It then finds the true nearest node to the cursor.
If the search area doesn't include any nodes it expands the area until a node is found.

The nearest-node search actually works in two phases. The first pass computes the initial nearest distance from leaf
entries in the R-tree, and the second pass runs a refined search within that radius to confirm the true closest node.
This avoids returning a node that was only nearest in the first coarse bounding-box expansion. I also exposed the
R-tree MBR data through helper methods so that the bounding-box debug visualization could draw the actual tree node
rectangles on screen, not just the viewport box.

I then started working on the UI of our application. I started by creating a hotkey to toggle on and off the
viewport debugging mode. After that was working I made another hotkey to toggle on and off the bounding boxes. When
both the viewport and bounding box debugging modes were finished, I started working on a way to toggle the visited
nodes when a path was found. This was mainly created to confirm that the A* algorithm was working as intended.

