// BENCHMARKING
After that was done I benchmarked the performance of the A* algorithm and the Dijkstra algorithm using the Mark8
solution. I later found a way to make better microbenchmarking and spent a lot of time learning how to do that properly.

The better approach was JMH, the Java Microbenchmark Harness. I set up a PathfinderBenchmark with proper @Benchmark
annotations, a PathfinderBenchmarkRunner to execute it and write CSV output, and a PathfinderBenchmarkUtils class to
load real map data for the benchmarks. I also contributed to the shared tree benchmarking infrastructure with
TreeBuildBenchmark, TreeSearchBenchmark, and AbstractTreeBenchmark as a common base class. Running real OSM data
through JMH gave much more reliable numbers than the custom timing approach, and the results were exported to
spreadsheets for comparison across algorithms and configurations.

// TESTS
I wrote unit tests throughout the project to validate the pathfinding logic. TestAdjacency covers the graph construction
side — checking that addEdge, connectTwoWay, and the adjacency-list structure behave correctly. TestPathfinder validates
the actual shortest-path results on small graphs where the correct answer can be verified by hand, including cases
with direct edges, alternative routes, and weighted path selection.
